title: Wow, amazing and so simple!

review:
This is an amazing thing, being able to easily take an almost perfect picture and make it what it should have been.  

Sometimes composition and lighting isn't all that is required to make that perfect picture.  Sometimes it is removing that person from the beach. (You know the one, who sees you taking a picture and insists on standing middle frame)

Thanks for this. Easy and fun.  

Well done!

title: Essential app in my photo manupulation arsenal
author: R.Leonardo
review:
I don't use that often, but is a real treat to have when needed. Does a surprisingly good job!  
Having no restrictions to zooming and image size is excellent.  

The thing that looses a star is that when trying to work on the edge of a photo, the app does not allow one to do so with ease.  The image always snaps the edge so it is very difficult, sometimes impossible to work on the very outer edge of an exposure to make corrections and I have to use a less accurate app to do some cloning/healing.
Fix that and it is 5 stars for sure!

review:

With that in mind, if you go slow and focus on the small details, it works pretty well!

title: Very useful little app, but‚Ä¶

review:
This a great little app that works well for a quick tidy up of an pic, but it saves the images with a naming convention that doesn‚Äôt seem to fit Apple‚Äôs requirements, regardless of saving a copy, or modifying an original.

When I check the images on my iPad with an Exif viewer app, it shows all images saved from TouchRetouch as having the name ‚Äòimage.jpg‚Äô. When connecting my iPad to my Mac desktop machine, the Image Capture app doesn‚Äôt even see those ‚Äòimage.jpg‚Äô files, so I can‚Äôt transfer them.

I need to use a 3rd party MacOS app (iMazing) which does show the images, so I can eventually download the pics to my desktop that way. A bit of an odd glitch in an otherwise useful little app.

title: Exceeded my expectations
author: 3ddCh
review:
I don‚Äôt usually write reviews but decided to write this one because I wanted to add some perspective from a pro‚Äôs point of view as some of the negative reviews almost made me overlook this app.

As a professional photographer and designer with decades of experience retouching in both analogue and digital media, this low cost app does actually do what it claims to do. 

It makes the simple retouching tasks very quick and easy ‚Äì but it is still highly capable of tackling the more complicated tasks like removing things from complex backgrounds with a clone tool that‚Äôs got some decent fine tuning controls. It‚Äôs not a perfect app but for something that costs a fraction of the likes of Affinity Photo‚Äînever mind Adobe Photoshop‚Äîit does an amazing job. My experience of using this app so far has put most of the negative reviews into, laughable, context and highlights those users‚Äô lack of understanding of what the app can do ‚Äì rather than the app‚Äôs actual shortcomings. 

This is possibly the best, specifically, retouching app I have used on the iPhone. That said I would like to see some form of blur tool and a patch tool added to its toolbox.

title: Really easy to use and fast results
author: C0ventryclare
review:
A friend recommended this app and as a Photoshop user I was  

It‚Äôs not photoshop but it doesn‚Äôt claim to be ‚Äì it has been built to target those inconvenient objects in the background of photos and clears them away, even those thin telephone wires that spoil many a sunset snap.

A great tool for those who love to post photos of their own children, but without causing concern to the parents of other children in the picture.

COVID has meant no parents and roughly four children to a group at our local nursery.  The teacher sent a photo to Mum but she couldn‚Äôt share it because of other children in the picture, so she gave me her phone and about 5 minutes later none of the other children could be identified. Another 15 minutes and there was a cream background with birthday boy sitting at a table on his own, with a big cake and a grin‚Ä¶ 

The more it‚Äôs used and the longer time spent on a job the better the results.

If developers would like another beta-tester any time, please let me know!

title: Incredible
author: Espekayen
review:
This is very impressive stuff. The clone stamp is amazing but will take some getting used to; watch the included videos to get an idea of how to make the most of this great feature. The written instructions are also pretty good so make sure you read them!

Your results will vary, depending on the photo you're working on and its complexity. I've gotten some mixed results from TouchRetouch but overall I am very happy with it. The lasso feature is also very handy and works well for the most part.

Bear in mind that the app will save your work at a maximum resolution of 1825 by 1369 pixels. I wish there was an option to save at the iPhone's native resolution but it's not a major issue for me.

For 59p, this is excellent. By all means try the free version; I can virtually guarantee you'll be so impressed with it that you'll end up paying for the full version.

TouchRetouch is not perfect by any means, but the impressive functionality you get for 59p is incredible and it has to be worth five stars.

review:
I have used this app for a long time and have been amazed at what I can do with it. If you take a bit to learn what happens when you try certain things, then take your time when doing an edit, you can get some pretty incredible results. I‚Äôve learned that object removal on a complex background can be most difficult, but that is the same on expensive products. 

Wish List: I would love Apple Pencil support on the iPad version for more precise selections and would purchase a new version to get it. The ability to edit in layers would also be incredible and worth more money. Finally, I would also love to copy and paste an area in addition to using the cloning tool to make some edits easier. 
 
Kudos the the developers!

title: Brilliant
author: AmyB8484
review:
This app is amazing. Way ahead of any other app like it on the App Store. It‚Äôs comparable to the desktop Photoshop Content Aware Fill feature, which, before, I could only access by transferring the photo to my computer and pulling up Photoshop on desktop, which was a headache, as this feature is not available on mobile Photoshop. It‚Äôs actually faster and simpler to use than the Photoshop version. 

It has so many uses, and has enabled me to use photos that otherwise would have been unusable. I want to post a pic online of my house, but my house is messy or something is dirty? I can remove the mess, or spots and stains with this app. I was editing pics for my sister‚Äôs flower business for her Instagram, but needed to get rid of the customers‚Äô personal info printed on the bouquet cards. Wiped them right off, and this app made the cards look perfectly blank. It looked so realistic, it looked like the bouquets just had blank cards attached to them. Nature photo with ugly power lines? This app takes them right out, and it looks like they were never there. 

Of course this app can only be expected to do so much because it‚Äôs not magic. It works best when what you‚Äôre trying to erase is surrounded by blank, uniform space, or at least simple objects. If it‚Äôs surrounded by a lot of objects, the app won‚Äôt always know what to do. In those cases, you‚Äôre better off removing things manually, like with the clone stamp feature. But I‚Äôd say 75% of the tine, this app works for me, and does a far better job than any other app. It‚Äôs great for removing blemishes on a face portrait, and I‚Äôll use this on a portrait first before then continuing in another beauty editing app because it does a much better job. 

Overall, this is one of my staples for photo editing. It‚Äôs saved me loads of time. You won‚Äôt find a comparable app or a general editing app that does a comparable job at object removal.

title: Simple and very effective.
author: Stoshlee
review:
I am an experienced amateur photographer, and usually use Lightroom for all my post processing.  This was recommended to me by a fellow photographer, so I thought I'd give it a try.  It really is impressive.  With very little effort I can eliminate unwanted objects with a simple swipe.  Power lines that have previously been a chore to remove, can now effectively be eliminated with a single operation ... just mark the offending line and it disappears.  In most cases, but not all, there are no artifacts left that I can see.

The finished work can be saved as a copy, which is very important to me.  This is a really good product, and a bargain for its cheap price.  I highly recommend it.  BTW, the current version is 100% stable on my iPad Pro 2020.

title: When Ineptness Meets A Good App
author: unidyn
review:
It‚Äôs sad to see negative comments that blame this app for not working as they hoped. I‚Äôve used this app for almost three years and it does work very well.

When you choose an object to remove and it is surrounded with similar background this app works beautifully. There are scenarios where an object to be removed borders two or more dissimilar backgrounds and this is a problem for any removal program I‚Äôve encountered because it relies on surrounding pixels to replace the object. It stands to reason if you have multiple backgrounds around the object you want to remove you will see them in the replacement. I have worked at spending time with problem scenarios like this and had pretty good outcomes but we‚Äôre talking patience, trial & error, and maybe up to 30 minutes to get there. If you‚Äôre lazy and can‚Äôt be bothered to work through tough removal situations don‚Äôt blame the app. 

Have a chair on the beach you need to remove? Easy and 100% effective because the sand around the chair fills in for a perfect cover. If you want to remove a guitar next to a person you can, but if the person is wearing the guitar, this app, or any other, can not do that and replace the body where it didn‚Äôt exist before, nor can it avoid filling in without adding whatever is around the guitar. And lastly, people fail to get a result when they‚Äôre heavy-handed and get poor results. Reasonable people see that some tasks require more finesse and patience to get good results. 

This app succeeds well at its claim. It‚Äôs a tool as good as the user‚Äôs ability and judgement at what‚Äôs reasonable to accomplish. For every 10 pictures you edit you‚Äôll be amazed with at least 7-8 of them where as 2-3 may be unhelp-able because of the photo‚Äôs surroundings. I give it an enthusiastic 5 stars for the dozens of photos it turned from mediocre to unbelievably great because of what it reasonable CAN do.

title: PFM!
author: The Fire Horse
review:
This one deserves your attention! I‚Äôve used photoshop from the days it fit on a floppy disk. I never thought I‚Äôd see an automated tool that I would trust with my retouching.
This thing is just amazing. It has some built in magic to determine how to fill an area. It does in seconds what used to take hours manually, and the results don‚Äôt exhibit any obvious repeat.
It doesn‚Äôt always get it right the first time, maybe it picks up too much background, or leaves some leftover pieces, but it is so fast you can just undo and try again with a slightly different selection or brush size.  I‚Äôve noticed that small differences in the original selection can produce wildly different results.

I wish we could post before and after photos here. It has saved a few vacation photos that had a finger partially blocking the lens.  I wasn‚Äôt expecting much when I first tried it, then almost fell over, ‚Äúwhere did it get all that replacement sky, with clouds even?!‚Äù

title: Thank You For Transparent Editing
author: Joshua D.
review:
I've owned and used Touch Retouch since the very first version and when I was on Instagram I recommended it to hundreds of people who all bought the app.

And I've always loved how beautifully I think that this app works. Sure, it's not going to be perfect every time you remove something. But, that's why the developer offers tools like the Cloning function in this program, to fix smudged and distorted backgrounds. All it takes in my opinion is just some trial and error to get good at using this application. With my long use of the app with the app now, I really cannot think of anything that I can't remove satisfactorily. 

I'd recommend to just use all the options here and play around with the app for a bit. It might take some trial and error to get the results you want. But I'd advise to just be patient and familiarize yourself with all the tools here. And also possibly look up some tutorials on somewhere like YouTube from the developer or other pro users to learn how to properly use Touch Retouch. I can promise you that for removing objects from photos, there is no substitute or anything close to this app in my opinion. At least not on mobile devices, that's for sure I think. I've tried pretty much most of competing apps to see what they offered and they are straight trash I believe compared to Touch Retouch. It's no contest in my book. I mean, I do wish that sometimes I didn't have to spend extra time using the Cloning tool to fix distortions. 

But, really, considering the seemingly magical I things I believe this app does for me and everyone else. Well, I find that extra work to be a serious and completely acceptable condition, honestly. Plus, I'd be a unhappy with the results of this app if other features like the Cloning tool weren't offered. So I truly cannot complain about any facet of this magic app at all.

Really, though, to be able to do any of this in a mobile app. Which is something that you used to have to have high end computers and then later Photoshop to do this. Well, I find it extraordinary what this program can accomplish. Again, just familiarize yourself to the different tools offered like the Cloning option, to easily clean up distortions and smudges. They also offer the option for you to adjust the opacity and size of each brush and tool used. Which, I believe, that this adds even more help and options in cleaning up background distortions from removals. 

If you use a brush that is giving too harsh of a result. Just click on the option to adjust the brush settings (I believe it's the icon with the 3 horizontal lines in it) and play around with lowering the opacity of the brush and tools (basically meaning how much of the brush is put down on the photo) and then retry whatever your working on. You might find that adjusting those settings for each brush or tool helps a whole lot, I sure have always found that to be very true.

Also, previously in Touch Retouch, when you imported an image with a transparent background, oh boy, the app didn't like that at all, haha. About 99% of the time with a transparent image that you edited here, the app would randomly add big swaths of solid black artifacts to your exported transparent image. And, man, that was a huge pain in the butt I always found to remove that crud. I'd always have to go use one of image eraser apps when this happened and spend forever removing the black artifacts from my rendered photos. It always added so much more time to any given project I was working on.

Now, though, I'm happy to attest and report that the new function of allowing us to edit transparent photos works wonderfully I think. I just cannot thank the developer of this program enough for adding this invaluable new function to Touch Retouch, thank you. I was able to import and load up a transparent image and the app doesn't attach any of those solid black artifacts anymore! I am extremely overjoyed! Woohoo :D! Thank you!

Plus, as I've detailed above, I believe that this app is remarkable in what it allows you to do. I've seen and used other apps in the past that claim to work as well as Touch Retouch and to me they are extremely pale imitations. They don't offer the sophistication or quality of the editing engine in this app in my opinion. For me with those lousy competitor apps, it's the difference between buying a McRib from McDonald's to eat or going all out and buying filet mignon from a swanky restaurant. I believe that's the difference between Touch Retouch and really any other app on the App Store that claims to properly remove objects from photographs. It's no contest in the end in my mind.

So, again, I'd like to sincerely thank the developer for this incredible application, for all your continued hard work and dedication to improving and this program and most especially for the new transparent image editing update. And to other users who might be frustrated at first with Touch Retouch. Like I said, avail yourself to the other tools offered here besides just the main removal function, like the Cloning tool.

Also, if you just need objects like telephone lines removed from a photograph. Man, that one tool the app offers specifically for removing thin lines from photos is exceptionally up to that task in my opinion, give it a try and see what I mean. Well, thanks, again to the developer for all of the above and God bless.

iPhone 8 Plus
iOS 12.4.1
